      "text": "[[Harold Abelson]] and [[Gerald Sussman]], in [[Structure And Interpretation Of Computer Programs]], and [[Paul Graham]], in [[On Lisp]], both strongly make the point that far from thinking of the language as immutable, you should think of all programming as language design.  After designing the correct language, the solution to the original problem is usually clear, concise, and correct.  Graham argues (convincingly) that Lisp is an ideal vehicle for designing such \"embedded\" languages.",
      "id": "b008f8037bb1a95de5aae888cc5241bb"
